We found this leopard as it was sleeping in a tree and we sat with it for some time. Then finally, for a brief moment, it opened up its eyes. I feel fortunate to have captured a shot while it took a look around before returning to sleep. Such a beautiful animal!

On our final morning we did one more pass along the Sand River looking for a Leopard that we had a few days prior. While searching we came across two male lions and one female sitting next to a Water buck they caught the night before. This one was sitting under the bush with what was left of the meal.
I can’t wait to go back to Africa!
Ending the morning with a big yawn ready for some sleep! 💤 🦁 #lioness

The fog is a double edge sword to me. I love the photographs that I create on foggy days but those days can also make it harder to find whales!

The worlds been flooded with short form video content since the pandemic and photography is something I kind of set aside to keep up with “algorithms” to promote my private whale watching business but I’ll tell you what there is something about taking a photo that just feels amazing!  If you are a photographer I run small private whale watching trips for a couple people to get an amazing perspective on the bay. If you are interested in photographing some whales click the link in my bio and come see some whales.

It’s crazy how I took this photo in 2016 and it’s still one of my favorite photos I’ve ever taken! Will I ever get something like this again?! I hope so… ❤️

I want be honest. I have lots of photos and videos from trips I’ve been on over the years that I never post. In the last 10 years I’ve built my brand and business photographing whales and I think I’ve always been worried if I post content other than whales I won’t be able to sell my whale watching trips and continue to grow my brand. I realize that I have to start posting for me instead of what does “well” on my page. I love all nature and wildlife and trying to stick to my niche of whales can sometimes put me into a rut and when I take a break and photograph other subjects it brings back my motivation. I hope you enjoy the sprinkled in different content on my page. Just a thought good morning and here’s a beautiful lioness from Africa!
Saw Google for the first time in almost two years today! He put on an incredible display of power!
El Capitan! This was such a cool spot to shoot! I had a lot of fun photographing in Yosemite definitely want to go back soon!

social_posts.post_text: New goal unlocked! I need to visit @churchillwildsafaris in the winter and see wolves in the snow!
What’s your favorite animal to film on the ocean or land?

Incredible afternoon! We saw lots of whales but they were very spread out. We also saw 100 Pacific white-sided dolphins, 50 common dolphins, and Risso’s dolphins I left out of the video. Also if you read this caption this video was from yesterday! Comment your favorite clip out of the three!
Humpbacks, Orcas, and good ocean conditions yesterday!

The R5 is perfect for these crazy moments to be able to capture both video and photo!

What do you shoot on?

I use the C70 and R5
@canonusa

I love when Humpbacks turn as they are diving a lot of the times it’s because they are circling back down to food!
I was so stoked to see the sea lion swim right over the Humpback whales head. I accidentally touched focus on my monitor and it started out of focus unfortunately but still really cool to see.

How I layer sound for my whale videos!
1. Add general ambience 
2. Add sounds of secondary animals in the frame
3. Add the crashing of waves to sound like the whale breaching the surface.
If you want a more in depth video Let me know.
